<body>
<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>

<p>A <rs type="material" key="marmor">white marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">altar</rs> (<measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">0.305</measure> at top, <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">0.265</measure> centre, <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">0.35</measure> at base × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">0.84</measure> × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="depth">0.56</measure>) with moulding above and below on three sides, which has been cut away on the left side. The back is rough.</p></div><div type="description" n="text"><head>Description of Text</head><p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> (l. 1) on the upper moulding, and (ll. 2-5) on the face, above a relief of a <rs type="decoration">swag</rs> with a <rs type="decoration">pendant object</rs>.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="letters">
<head>Letters</head>
<p><measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.0175–0.024</measure>; square <term lang="la">sigma</term>, lunate <term lang="la">omega</term></p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="date">
<head>Date</head>
<p>
<date notBefore="0001" notAfter="0300" exact="none">First to third centuries A.D.</date> (<rs type="criteria">terminology</rs>)</p>
</div>
<div type="edition" lang="grc">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="θεός">θεοῖς</w> <w lemma="ἐπήκοος">ἐπηκόοις</w><lb n="2"/> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Εὐάνθης">Εὐάνθης</name></persName> <w lemma="καί">κ<supplied reason="omitted">α</supplied>ὶ</w><lb n="3"/> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Φιλήτης">Φιλήτη</name></persName> <w lemma="ὁ">οἱ</w> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Ἑρμίας">Ἑρμί<lb n="4" type="worddiv"/>ου</name></persName> <w lemma="ὑπέρ">ὑπὲρ</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τῶν</w> <w lemma="ἴδιος">ἰ<lb n="5" type="worddiv"/>δίων</w>  <w lemma="εὐχή">εὐχήν</w></ab>
</div>


<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>To the gods who listen: Euanthes and Philete, children of Hermias <supplied reason="subaudible">paid</supplied> the <rs type="subject">vow</rs> for their family.</p>
</div>
